question:
District category contains Suburban Neighborhood, Single-family Homes, and Administrative District.
Supermarkets category contains Big Lots, Target, and Fresh Thyme Market.
The number of each Suburban Neighborhood 's Fresh Thyme Market equals 7 more than each Suburban Neighborhood 's Big Lots.
The number of each Single-family Homes 's Big Lots equals 0 more than each Single-family Homes 's Fresh Thyme Market.
The number of each Administrative District 's Big Lots equals each Suburban Neighborhood 's Supermarkets.
The number of each Single-family Homes 's Fresh Thyme Market equals 4 times each Single-family Homes 's Target.
The number of each Single-family Homes 's Target equals 10.
The number of each Suburban Neighborhood 's Target equals 12 times each Administrative District 's Target.
The number of each Administrative District 's Target equals 14.
The number of each Administrative District 's Fresh Thyme Market equals the sum of each Administrative District 's Big Lots, each Suburban Neighborhood 's Supermarkets, each Administrative District 's Target, and each Single-family Homes 's Target.
The number of each Suburban Neighborhood 's Big Lots equals 15 more than the sum of each Suburban Neighborhood 's Target and each Administrative District 's Target.
How many Big Lots does Administrative District have?
solution:
Define each Administrative District 's Target as i; So i = 14.
Define each Suburban Neighborhood 's Target as W; So W = 12 * i = 12 * 14 = 7.
Define each Suburban Neighborhood 's Big Lots as y; J = W + i = 7 + 14 = 21; So y = 15 + J = 15 + 21 = 13.
Define each Suburban Neighborhood 's Fresh Thyme Market as Z; So Z = 7 + y = 7 + 13 = 20.
Define each Suburban Neighborhood 's Supermarkets as c; A = Z + y = 20 + 13 = 10; So c = W + A = 7 + 10 = 17.
Define each Administrative District 's Big Lots as v; So v = c = 17.
